Common Ports and Protocols	
	

TCP: TRANSMISSION CONTROL PROTOCOL/INTERNET PROTOCOL
     The purpose of TCP/IP is to allow communication over large distances

TCP/IP is a layered server architecture system in which each layer is defined according to a specific function to perform. 
All these four TCP/IP layers work collaboratively to transmit the data from one layer to another.

	  TCP/IP                            OSI Model

	Application Layer------------------Application
                         ------------------Presentation
			 ------------------Session

	Transport Layer  ------------------Transport
	Internet Layer   ------------------Network

	Network Interface------------------Data Link
			 ------------------Physical link



-FTP(21) : FILE TRANSFER PROTOCOL
-SSH(22) : CRYPTOGRAPHIC NETWORK PROTOCOL(SECURE SHELL)
-Telnet(23) : FOR VIRTUAL TERMINALS
-SMTP(25) : FOR EMAILS
-DNS(53) : DOMAIN NAME SYSTEM(NAMING SYSTEM FOR DEVICES CONNECTED TO NETWORK)
-HTTP(80) : FOR WEB SURFING
-HTTPS(443) : FOR WEB SURFING
-POP3(110) : POST OFFICE PROTOCOL(RETRIEVE EMAILS FROM MAIL SERVER)
-SMB(139+445)	
-IMAP(143)

UDP:

-DNS(53) : DOMAIN NAME SYSTEM(NAMING SYSTEM FOR DEVICES CONNECTED TO NETWORK)
-DHCP(67,68) : DYNAMIC HOST CONFIG PROTOCOL
-TFTP(69)
-SNMP(161)